text: Meeting with Agriculture Secretary to Discuss Continued Farm Bill Delays
label: BODY

text: On Wednesday, I met with Secretary of Agriculture Ed Shafer. This was my first time visiting with Secretary Shafer, who
label: BODY

text: took over as head of USDA in January. I took the opportunity to discuss the lack of progress on the farm bill and ideas
label: BODY

text: that would speed up passage of a bill. The Secretary and I agree that as spring planting begins and summer harvest
label: BODY

text: approaches, farmers need to know what type of farm policy they will be operating under in the current crop year.
label: BODY

text: Late this week, a preliminary framework was agreed to by the Chairmen and Ranking Members of the House and Senate
label: BODY

text: Agriculture Committee. We will know more about the framework as it is discussed in conference meetings over the course
label: BODY

text: of the next several days, but from what I can tell, the priorities in this farm bill certainly do not reflect those of farmers and
label: BODY

text: ranchers. Funding is being redirected out of programs that support producers and into non-agricultural programs. This is
label: BODY

text: further evidence of movement in a direction that is less friendly to farmers in Kansas and the small towns they live in. As
label: BODY

text: a member of the conference committee, I will be working to protect direct payments and the viability of crop insurance.
label: BODY

text: Because a bill was not passed this week, the farm bill was extended an additional week.
label: BODY

text: Congressman Jerry Moran

text: Voting to Delay Medicaid Regulations
label: BODY

text: The House approved legislation this week to delay the implementation of seven Medicaid regulations for one year.
label: BODY

text: Medicaid is a joint federal-state health insurance program for the poor. I am concerned these seven regulations would
label: BODY

text: push more Medicaid costs on the states, narrow certain services provided by Medicaid and limit some state services
label: BODY

text: eligible for federal reimbursements. Without congressional action to delay these new administrative rules, Kansas and
label: BODY

text: other states would be forced to pay for more of the health care costs associated with Medicaid. This legislation now goes
label: BODY

text: to the Senate for consideration.
label: BODY

text: Veterans' Benefits Bills Approved
label: BODY

text: I participated in a Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Economic Opportunity hearing this week that approved several
label: BODY

text: veterans' measures regarding housing, education and other benefits. The Subcommittee agreed to the Veterans
label: BODY

text: Education Improvement Act, a bill to improve veterans' educational benefits and modernize the Montgomery G.I. Bill.
label: BODY

text: This bill is the product of a series of Subcommittee hearings conducted since the beginning of last year to evaluate the
label: BODY

text: G.I. Bill and explore improvements. The G.I. Bill should be updated, both to recognize the increased role of our Guard
label: BODY

text: and Reserve members and to ensure that all veterans have the resources to attend school when they return from
label: BODY

text: service. I am hopeful Congress will act soon to modernize the G.I. Bill.
label: BODY

text: Discussing our Nation's Rail Infrastructure
label: BODY

text: On Wednesday, I attended a Transportation and Infrastructure Subcommittee on Railroads hearing to discuss rail
label: BODY

text: capacity for our nation's railroads. Freight railroads currently move more than 40 percent of our nation's freight. The
label: BODY

text: increase in demand for freight services is threatening to overload the current capacity of America's rail infrastructure.
label: BODY

text: Much of the investment in rail infrastructure is made by the railroads themselves. During the hearing, we listened to
label: BODY

text: various ideas on improving the amount of railroad track available throughout the country.
label: BODY

text: Testing New Vehicle Technology on Earth Day
label: BODY

text: Around the world on Tuesday, people marked Earth Day by taking time to consider ways to improve and protect our
label: BODY

text: environment. I had the opportunity to test drive a plug-in hybrid electric car. With new advances in technology, these cars
label: BODY

text: offer hope for reducing our dependence on foreign oil, cleaning up the environment and lowering fuel costs for American
label: BODY

text: consumers. Plug-in hybrids can be recharged in standard electrical outlets and driven up to 60 miles without the use of
label: BODY

text: gasoline. Statistics show the average American commutes 40 miles round trip each day. This technology would allow
label: BODY

text: such a person to drive all day without using any gas.
label: BODY

text: Our foreign policy is distorted because of our reliance on oil from other countries. Switching to new forms of
label: BODY

text: transportation that run on electricity or renewable fuels will make our country more secure and should help Kansans
label: BODY

text: struggling to afford gas for their vehicles.
label: BODY

text: Senate Reaches Deal on FAA Bill
label: BODY

text: As more Americans travel by air, our nation's aging aviation infrastructure system becomes even more strained. We
label: BODY

text: need a modern air traffic control system that can handle the increase in passengers in a safe and efficient manner. In
label: BODY

text: September, I supported House passage of legislation to modernize the air traffic control system and fund the Federal
label: BODY

text: Aviation Administration (FAA) through 2011. While this bill passed the House, it had been stalled in the Senate. This
label: BODY

text: week, an agreement was reached that will bring this bill to a vote in the next few days. Importantly, the Senate
label: BODY

text: agreement does not include user-fees on general aviation. I worked successfully in the House to defeat a similar
label: BODY

text: proposal that would have increased general aviation user fees. Many of the general aviation aircraft and parts are made
label: BODY

text: in Kansas and this user fee proposal would have harmed the local and state economy, as well as individual pilots across
label: BODY

text: the state.
label: BODY

text: Attending the Kansas State Society Cherry Blossom Banquet
label: BODY

text: On Tuesday, I joined Kansans for the annual Kansas Society of Washington, D.C., Cherry Blossom Banquet. The event
label: BODY

text: in D.C. was a great opportunity to meet many Kansans who work in our nation's capital to preserve our way of life back
label: BODY

text: home. I was honored to introduce the 2008 Kansan of the Year, Kroger Chairman and CEO Dave Dillon. Dillon was
label: BODY

text: recognized for his leadership in working to rebuild the Dillons/KWIK Shop convenience and grocery store in Greensburg
label: BODY

text: following the deadly tornado last year. Dillon's great-grandfather, J.S. Dillon, opened the first Dillon's grocery store in
label: BODY

text: Hutchinson nearly a century ago. Congratulations also to the 2008 Kansas Cherry Blossom Princess Justine Sterling,
label: BODY

text: originally of Kiowa.
label: BODY

text: I visited the Lewis and Clark Center at Fort Leavenworth this week. This was my first visit to the Lewis and Clark Center
label: BODY

text: since its opening in August 2007. The Lewis and Clark Center is the new home for the Command and General Staff
label: BODY

text: College, which serves as a graduate school for approximately 1,200 Army majors and international military leaders.
label: BODY

text: Following a tour of the facility, I met with Lieutenant General William Caldwell and State Representative Kenny Wilk.
label: BODY

text: Visiting Children's Mercy Hospital in Kansas City
label: BODY

text: En route back to Washington, D.C., this week, I visited Children's Mercy Hospital in Kansas City for a tour of the hospital
label: BODY

text: and to meet with members of the staff and Board of Directors. Children's Mercy Hospital is a comprehensive pediatric
label: BODY

text: medical center and is ranked as one of the leading children's hospitals in the nation. It is the only Level I Pediatric
label: BODY

text: Trauma Center located between St. Louis and Denver. Medical professionals provide care for children from birth to age
label: BODY

text: I was impressed with the family-centered environment and the care they not only provide to the child, but also the
label: BODY

text: support available for the families. The hospital staff shared with me several interesting statistics, including the fact that
label: BODY

text: nearly one-fourth of all Kansas children admitted to any hospital are admitted to Children's Mercy. In 2007, Children's
label: BODY

text: Mercy provided care for children from 101 of the 105 Kansas counties. Children's Mercy also operates a primary care
label: BODY

text: clinic in Wyandotte County, a full service general pediatrics hospital in Overland Park and has outreach clinics in Hays,
label: BODY

text: Manhattan, Pittsburg, Salina, Wichita and Junction City. Click here to view photos from my visit.
label: BODY
